Trump and the Economy
New York — Financial markets have finally come to terms with the reality that Donald Trump is the U.S. president.
The world has endured two years of reckless tweets and public statements from the most powerful person in the world. The obvious question is, what has kept this going for so long?
On one hand, up until now, investors have been treating Trump as someone who only makes noise but doesn't deliver results.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies favorable to the corporate sector and shareholders, they are willing to grant him the benefit of the doubt.
Many people believe that in the end, the "adults in the room" will rein in Trump and ensure that government policies stay within bounds.
Such assumptions were more or less validated during the first year of Trump's presidency, a period during which economic growth and expected corporate profit increases—due to upcoming tax cuts and deregulation—led to a strong stock market performance.
In 2017, the U.S. stock indices rose by more than 20%.
But in 2018, the situation took a sharp turn for the worse, especially in the final months.
Despite the company's profits increasing by over 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the U.S. stock market fluctuated throughout most of the year and is now sharply declining.
Currently, various indices are in correction territory (i.e., down 10% from their recent highs), and technology stock indices (such as the Nasdaq) have fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Although the increased volatility in financial markets reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging economies, the recent turmoil is due to Trump.
At the start of this year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which ended up pushing up long-term interest rates and pushing an economy already near full employment to its peak.
By February, concerns that inflation would rise above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% triggered the first wave of risk aversion in 2018.
Next, Trump launched a trade war against China and other major American trading partners.
Concerns about government protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year, but are now reaching a new peak.
Recent U.S. actions toward China appear to be preparing for a comprehensive cold war involving trade, economics, and geopolitics.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies could lead to stagflation (weakened growth combined with increased inflation).
After all, Trump is prepared to restrict foreign direct investment and has implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will hinder the growth of the labor supply in the context of an aging workforce and increasingly severe skill mismatches.
Furthermore, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure plan aimed at stimulating private sector productivity or accelerating the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other occasions, Trump has consistently criticized businesses' hiring, production, investment, and pricing practices, especially technology companies, which already face widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also been impacted by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening raised short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies experienced capital flight and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports have suffered losses due to the decline in commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade relations with China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy has created volatility.
The U.S. reinstatement of sanctions against Iran drove up oil prices. Subsequently, the U.S. government revoked exemptions and pressured Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, leading to a sharp drop in oil prices.
Although American consumers benefit from low oil prices, the stock prices of American energy companies cannot be sustained.
In addition, excessive fluctuations in oil prices are detrimental to both producers and consumers, as they hinder sound investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, it is now evident that almost all the benefits from last year's tax cuts have flowed to the corporate sector, rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means that household consumption may soon slow down, further affecting the economy.
However, the primary cause of the recent sharp decline in both U.S. and global stock markets in the latest quarter was President Trump's own statements and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (despite his recent "ceasefire" agreement with Chinese President Xi Jinping) is Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve. His attacks began in the spring of 2018, when the U.S. economic growth rate was above 4%.
Due to these earlier criticisms, the market became a nervous wreck when the Fed correctly decided to raise interest rates this month, while also hinting that rate hikes would be slower in 2019.
More likely, the relatively hawkish stance of the Federal Reserve is a reaction to Trump's criticisms of it.
Facing a hostile presidential tweet, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needs to send a signal that the central bank remains politically independent.
But then, because Congress refused to fund his useless Mexican border wall, Trump decided to shut down the federal government partially.
This move pushed the market into a near-panic state. Soon after the government shutdown, reports emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — a move that could turn a market correction into a crash.
On the eve of the Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to reassure the markets.
He claimed that Trump had no plan to fire Powell, and that the U.S. fiscal condition was sound, which precisely highlights the question of whether the situation is truly as good as it seems.
Recent internal government personnel changes, which may not necessarily affect economic decision-making, have also caused concern in the markets.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave, leaving the Trump administration with no sane individuals.
The rest will be entirely economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks, following Trump's lead without question.
Currently, the possibility of a comprehensive geopolitical conflict with China cannot be ruled out.
A new Cold War is highly likely to lead to deglobalization and disrupt global supply chains, but the technology industry will be the first to suffer, as evidenced by recent cases involving ZTE and Huawei.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO amid economic and political instability in Europe.
The investigation by Special Counsel Robert Mueller into the relationship between Trump's 2016 presidential campaign and Russia has been a Damocles' sword hanging over President Trump's career.
Trump is now the Dr. Strangelove of financial markets.
Like the paranoid madmen in Stanley Kubrick's classic films, he is deeply trapped in a mutually assured economic destruction from which he cannot escape.
Nowadays, the market has recognized this danger, and the risks of a financial crisis and global recession are rising sharply.
